{"parentUuid":"f3759a50-296a-456b-9cf5-560319f812b2","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_017XX9ZB6ezUinxmipn8LLMR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01AShS4eGH4Mzv1gc2Q3rTEL","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"counterfactual evaluation perturbation reasoning memorization vs reasoning benchmark"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5912,"cache_read_input_tokens":6421,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5912,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":8306}}},"requestId":"req_011CcFqLQeBeU7tpFCv5d2Gu","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"c294b88e-6c46-48fb-9908-b4164f2a3044","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:15.613Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"f3759a50-296a-456b-9cf5-560319f812b2","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QkquN98Jw5vDFqPusqPU1S","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"benchmark data contamination decontamination LLM evaluation detection\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"LLM Benchmark Datasets Should Be Contamination-Resistant\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2605.19999v1\"},{\"title\":\"LLM-as-an-Interviewer: Beyond Static Testing Through Dynamic LLM Evaluation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.10424\"},{\"title\":\"Detecting Data Contamination in LLMs via In-Context Learning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.27055v1\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - lyy1994/awesome-data-contamination: The Paper List on Data Contamination for Large Language Models Evaluation. · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/lyy1994/awesome-data-contamination\"},{\"title\":\"Inference-Time Decontamination: Reusing Leaked Benchmarks for Large   Language Model Evaluation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.13990\"},{\"title\":\"Benchmark Data Contamination of Large Language Models: A Survey\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2406.04244v1\"},{\"title\":\"DCR: Quantifying Data Contamination in LLMs Evaluation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2507.11405\"},{\"title\":\"Reusing Leaked Benchmarks for Large Language Model ...\",\"url\":\"https://aclanthology.org/2024.findings-emnlp.532.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"When Benchmarks Leak: Inference-Time Decontamination for LLMs\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.19334v1\"}]\n\nI've completed the web search for your query about benchmark data contamination, decontamination, LLM evaluation, and detection. Here's a summary of what I found:\n\n## Key Topics Covered\n\n**Data Contamination in LLMs:**\nLLMs are trained on large corpora that can be contaminated with benchmark data, undermining benchmark reliability. Test set contamination occurs when test samples or their close variants leak into training data and artificially inflate reported performance.\n\n**Contamination Detection Methods:**\nTraditional contamination detection methods directly calculate the overlap between pre-training data and evaluation datasets, including n-gram analysis and BM25 for indexing and matching. Detection typically involves dataset inspection, membership inference, and example generation. There is significant interest in contamination detection.\n\n**Decontamination Approaches:**\nDecontamination involves avoiding or mitigating the negative effects of contamination, typically applied in the training phase where model developers remove overlaps between pre-training data and evaluation data. Inference-Time Decontamination (ITD) addresses this issue by detecting and rewriting leaked samples without altering their difficulties, and can mitigate performance inflation caused by memorizing leaked benchmarks.\n\n**Current Challenges:**\nEfforts to prevent contamination through detection have had limited success, prompting researchers to focus on contamination mitigation in benchmarks.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"ed2a3cb3-6655-4c3a-ad2b-9090fe77f9b6","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:24.102Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"benchmark data contamination decontamination LLM evaluation detection","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01MFU3UsLhctL5g1c1iWeVKp","content":[{"title":"LLM Benchmark Datasets Should Be Contamination-Resistant","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2605.19999v1"},{"title":"LLM-as-an-Interviewer: Beyond Static Testing Through Dynamic LLM Evaluation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.10424"},{"title":"Detecting Data Contamination in LLMs via In-Context Learning","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.27055v1"},{"title":"GitHub - lyy1994/awesome-data-contamination: The Paper List on Data Contamination for Large Language Models Evaluation. · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/lyy1994/awesome-data-contamination"},{"title":"Inference-Time Decontamination: Reusing Leaked Benchmarks for Large   Language Model Evaluation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.13990"},{"title":"Benchmark Data Contamination of Large Language Models: A Survey","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2406.04244v1"},{"title":"DCR: Quantifying Data Contamination in LLMs Evaluation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2507.11405"},{"title":"Reusing Leaked Benchmarks for Large Language Model ...","url":"https://aclanthology.org/2024.findings-emnlp.532.pdf"},{"title":"When Benchmarks Leak: Inference-Time Decontamination for LLMs","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.19334v1"}]},"I've completed the web search for your query about benchmark data contamination, decontamination, LLM evaluation, and detection. Here's a summary of what I found:\n\n## Key Topics Covered\n\n**Data Contamination in LLMs:**\nLLMs are trained on large corpora that can be contaminated with benchmark data, undermining benchmark reliability. Test set contamination occurs when test samples or their close variants leak into training data and artificially inflate reported performance.\n\n**Contamination Detection Methods:**\nTraditional contamination detection methods directly calculate the overlap between pre-training data and evaluation datasets, including n-gram analysis and BM25 for indexing and matching. Detection typically involves dataset inspection, membership inference, and example generation. There is significant interest in contamination detection.\n\n**Decontamination Approaches:**\nDecontamination involves avoiding or mitigating the negative effects of contamination, typically applied in the training phase where model developers remove overlaps between pre-training data and evaluation data. Inference-Time Decontamination (ITD) addresses this issue by detecting and rewriting leaked samples without altering their difficulties, and can mitigate performance inflation caused by memorizing leaked benchmarks.\n\n**Current Challenges:**\nEfforts to prevent contamination through detection have had limited success, prompting researchers to focus on contamination mitigation in benchmarks."],"durationSeconds":8.486430083000101,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"f3759a50-296a-456b-9cf5-560319f812b2","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"c294b88e-6c46-48fb-9908-b4164f2a3044","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AShS4eGH4Mzv1gc2Q3rTEL","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"counterfactual evaluation perturbation reasoning memorization vs reasoning benchmark\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"On Memorization of Large Language Models in Logical Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.23123v1\"},{\"title\":\"CounterBench: LLM Counterfactual Benchmark\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/counterbench\"},{\"title\":\"CounterBench: A Benchmark for Counterfactuals Reasoning in Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2502.11008v1\"},{\"title\":\"CounterBench: Evaluating and Improving Counterfactual Reasoning in Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2502.11008v2\"},{\"title\":\"Rethinking RL Evaluation: Can Benchmarks Truly Reveal Failures of RL Methods?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.10541\"},{\"title\":\"On Memorization of Large Language Models in Logical Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2410.23123\"},{\"title\":\"CounterBench: A Benchmark for Counterfactuals Reasoning in Large   Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.11008\"},{\"title\":\"On Memorization of Large Language Models in Logical ...\",\"url\":\"https://aclanthology.org/2025.ijcnlp-long.148.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"MATH-Perturb: Benchmarking LLMs' Math Reasoning Abilities against Hard   Perturbations\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.06453\"},{\"title\":\"[2502.11008] CounterBench: Evaluating and Improving Counterfactual Reasoning in Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.11008\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding counterfactual evaluation, perturbation, reasoning, and memorization benchmarks:\n\n## Key Research Areas\n\n**Counterfactual Reasoning Benchmarks:**\n\nCounterBench is a comprehensive evaluation framework designed to assess counterfactual reasoning through 1.2K questions encompassing various domains and reasoning types, systematically evaluating five key dimensions to demand genuine reasoning beyond pattern recognition or memorized responses. It specifically assesses LLMs' ability to perform counterfactual inference using a set of formal rules, in contrast to previous studies that primarily focus on commonsense causal reasoning.\n\nVariable names use randomly generated tokens (e.g., \"Ziklo\", \"Blaf\") to prevent aliasing to memorized knowledge and enforce structural, context-independent reasoning.\n\n**Memorization vs. Reasoning Through Perturbations:**\n\nMemorization scores quantify performance variance under task perturbations, covering both counterfactual alterations (e.g., switching the roles of knights and knaves) and standard perturbations on language level and problem structure level. \n\nCounterfactual robustness tests reveal critical failures in models' ability to reason from novel premises, with severe performance degradation on counterfactual tests where accuracies drop from 74.8% and 64.2% to 41.2% and 36.0% respectively.\n\n**Perturbation-Based Evaluation Methods:**\n\nCounterfactual tests construct perturbed problems different from existing ones to test the generalization of LLMs and examine memorization effects.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"72511c81-ad5f-4a1a-b480-c916affdab07","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:29.451Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"counterfactual evaluation perturbation reasoning memorization vs reasoning benchmark","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_011rs5qcp7hpK1gQEQWVixyP","content":[{"title":"On Memorization of Large Language Models in Logical Reasoning","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.23123v1"},{"title":"CounterBench: LLM Counterfactual Benchmark","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/counterbench"},{"title":"CounterBench: A Benchmark for Counterfactuals Reasoning in Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2502.11008v1"},{"title":"CounterBench: Evaluating and Improving Counterfactual Reasoning in Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2502.11008v2"},{"title":"Rethinking RL Evaluation: Can Benchmarks Truly Reveal Failures of RL Methods?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.10541"},{"title":"On Memorization of Large Language Models in Logical Reasoning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2410.23123"},{"title":"CounterBench: A Benchmark for Counterfactuals Reasoning in Large   Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.11008"},{"title":"On Memorization of Large Language Models in Logical ...","url":"https://aclanthology.org/2025.ijcnlp-long.148.pdf"},{"title":"MATH-Perturb: Benchmarking LLMs' Math Reasoning Abilities against Hard   Perturbations","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.06453"},{"title":"[2502.11008] CounterBench: Evaluating and Improving Counterfactual Reasoning in Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.11008"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding counterfactual evaluation, perturbation, reasoning, and memorization benchmarks:\n\n## Key Research Areas\n\n**Counterfactual Reasoning Benchmarks:**\n\nCounterBench is a comprehensive evaluation framework designed to assess counterfactual reasoning through 1.2K questions encompassing various domains and reasoning types, systematically evaluating five key dimensions to demand genuine reasoning beyond pattern recognition or memorized responses. It specifically assesses LLMs' ability to perform counterfactual inference using a set of formal rules, in contrast to previous studies that primarily focus on commonsense causal reasoning.\n\nVariable names use randomly generated tokens (e.g., \"Ziklo\", \"Blaf\") to prevent aliasing to memorized knowledge and enforce structural, context-independent reasoning.\n\n**Memorization vs. Reasoning Through Perturbations:**\n\nMemorization scores quantify performance variance under task perturbations, covering both counterfactual alterations (e.g., switching the roles of knights and knaves) and standard perturbations on language level and problem structure level. \n\nCounterfactual robustness tests reveal critical failures in models' ability to reason from novel premises, with severe performance degradation on counterfactual tests where accuracies drop from 74.8% and 64.2% to 41.2% and 36.0% respectively.\n\n**Perturbation-Based Evaluation Methods:**\n\nCounterfactual tests construct perturbed problems different from existing ones to test the generalization of LLMs and examine memorization effects."],"durationSeconds":13.66477729200013,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c294b88e-6c46-48fb-9908-b4164f2a3044","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"ac114e13-69f7-498f-9175-d6e83a9f945a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01B6Pd3FpSenoxiz4UdFdcKg","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"compositional generalization split train test SCAN COGS systematic generalization\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Human-like systematic generalization through a meta-learning neural network | Nature\",\"url\":\"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06668-3\"},{\"title\":\"COGS: A Compositional Generalization Challenge Based on Semantic Interpretation | Request PDF\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/347232897_COGS_A_Compositional_Generalization_Challenge_Based_on_Semantic_Interpretation\"},{\"title\":\"Meta-Learning to Compositionally Generalize\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.04252\"},{\"title\":\"Towards Compositionally Generalizable Semantic Parsing in Large Language   Models: A Survey\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2404.13074\"},{\"title\":\"Compositional Program Generation for Few-Shot Systematic Generalization\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2309.16467v2\"},{\"title\":\"Towards Understanding the Relationship between In-context Learning and   Compositional Generalization\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2403.11834\"},{\"title\":\"Inducing Transformer's Compositional Generalization Ability via   Auxiliary Sequence Prediction Tasks\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2109.15256\"},{\"title\":\"Information Structure in Mappings: An Approach to Learning, Representation, and Generalisation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.23960\"},{\"title\":\"COGS: A Compositional Generalization Challenge Based on Semantic   Interpretation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2010.05465\"},{\"title\":\"Learning to Substitute Spans towards Improving Compositional   Generalization\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2306.02840\"}]\n\nI've found comprehensive information about compositional generalization, train-test splits, SCAN, COGS, and systematic generalization. Here's what the research shows:\n\n## SCAN and COGS Benchmarks\n\nSCAN contains a set of natural language commands and their corresponding action sequences, while COGS contains natural language sentences paired with logical forms based on lambda calculus and covers various systematic linguistic abstractions including examples of lexical and structural generalization.\n\n## Train-Test Splits\n\nSCAN uses Maximum Compound Divergence (MCD) splits, which are created based on the principle of maximizing the divergence between the compound distributions of the training and test sets. These splits capture a general notion of compositional generalization by capturing both systematicity and productivity, maximizing the divergence between the compounds while maintaining the closeness of the atom frequency distribution.\n\nCOGS provides a generalization (Gen) set drawn from a different distribution that specifically assesses compositional generalization, and was constructed based on various kinds of linguistic generalizations found in English, such as generalizing the subject role to the object role (systematicity) or generalizing to sentences with more depth (productivity).\n\n## Compositional Generalization Challenges\n\nSequence to Sequence models struggle at compositionality and systematic generalization, with the limitation attributed to their failure to internalize constructions conventionalized form meaning pairings that license productive recombination.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"85d086d9-41fe-463a-b024-3ebc570768ba","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:31.177Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"compositional generalization split train test SCAN COGS systematic generalization","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_0131ojBYsTVStXt7wZyx5BU3","content":[{"title":"Human-like systematic generalization through a meta-learning neural network | Nature","url":"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06668-3"},{"title":"COGS: A Compositional Generalization Challenge Based on Semantic Interpretation | Request PDF","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/347232897_COGS_A_Compositional_Generalization_Challenge_Based_on_Semantic_Interpretation"},{"title":"Meta-Learning to Compositionally Generalize","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.04252"},{"title":"Towards Compositionally Generalizable Semantic Parsing in Large Language   Models: A Survey","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2404.13074"},{"title":"Compositional Program Generation for Few-Shot Systematic Generalization","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2309.16467v2"},{"title":"Towards Understanding the Relationship between In-context Learning and   Compositional Generalization","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2403.11834"},{"title":"Inducing Transformer's Compositional Generalization Ability via   Auxiliary Sequence Prediction Tasks","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2109.15256"},{"title":"Information Structure in Mappings: An Approach to Learning, Representation, and Generalisation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.23960"},{"title":"COGS: A Compositional Generalization Challenge Based on Semantic   Interpretation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2010.05465"},{"title":"Learning to Substitute Spans towards Improving Compositional   Generalization","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2306.02840"}]},"I've found comprehensive information about compositional generalization, train-test splits, SCAN, COGS, and systematic generalization. Here's what the research shows:\n\n## SCAN and COGS Benchmarks\n\nSCAN contains a set of natural language commands and their corresponding action sequences, while COGS contains natural language sentences paired with logical forms based on lambda calculus and covers various systematic linguistic abstractions including examples of lexical and structural generalization.\n\n## Train-Test Splits\n\nSCAN uses Maximum Compound Divergence (MCD) splits, which are created based on the principle of maximizing the divergence between the compound distributions of the training and test sets. These splits capture a general notion of compositional generalization by capturing both systematicity and productivity, maximizing the divergence between the compounds while maintaining the closeness of the atom frequency distribution.\n\nCOGS provides a generalization (Gen) set drawn from a different distribution that specifically assesses compositional generalization, and was constructed based on various kinds of linguistic generalizations found in English, such as generalizing the subject role to the object role (systematicity) or generalizing to sentences with more depth (productivity).\n\n## Compositional Generalization Challenges\n\nSequence to Sequence models struggle at compositionality and systematic generalization, with the limitation attributed to their failure to internalize constructions conventionalized form meaning pairings that license productive recombination."],"durationSeconds":16.304539875000714,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ac114e13-69f7-498f-9175-d6e83a9f945a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
