{"parentUuid":"ea2da41e-2c8e-4518-a7b6-bc1503860f21","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Vz9L5a2U5JXUFCgdM1QsLJ","type":"tool_result","content":"# COGS Corpus Design for Compositional Generalization\n\nI cannot extract the specific COGS corpus design rules from the provided content, as the document appears to be a PDF with primarily encoded image and stream data rather than accessible text content about the COGS dataset.\n\nTo properly address your question about COGS's generalization set construction, specific test types, and memorization-prevention principles, I would need access to:\n\n1. The actual paper or documentation describing the COGS dataset architecture\n2. Clear text explaining the compositional splits and rules\n3. Details on generalization categories tested (e.g., length, depth, novel combinations)\n\n**What I can tell you:** COGS is a well-known compositional generalization benchmark designed to test whether models can handle novel compositional structures they haven't seen during training. The core principle involves systematically varying structural properties to ensure generalization requires compositional understanding rather than surface-level memorization.\n\nIf you have the actual research paper on COGS (likely \"Compositional Generalization via Semantic Parsing\" or related work), I'd be happy to extract the specific design principles, split methodology, and generalization test categories from that source directly.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 588.8KB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782018875944-xfuudb.pdf]"}]},"uuid":"6ebd7d57-d673-40fb-9664-7e79f5b16cbe","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:40.744Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":602974,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# COGS Corpus Design for Compositional Generalization\n\nI cannot extract the specific COGS corpus design rules from the provided content, as the document appears to be a PDF with primarily encoded image and stream data rather than accessible text content about the COGS dataset.\n\nTo properly address your question about COGS's generalization set construction, specific test types, and memorization-prevention principles, I would need access to:\n\n1. The actual paper or documentation describing the COGS dataset architecture\n2. Clear text explaining the compositional splits and rules\n3. Details on generalization categories tested (e.g., length, depth, novel combinations)\n\n**What I can tell you:** COGS is a well-known compositional generalization benchmark designed to test whether models can handle novel compositional structures they haven't seen during training. The core principle involves systematically varying structural properties to ensure generalization requires compositional understanding rather than surface-level memorization.\n\nIf you have the actual research paper on COGS (likely \"Compositional Generalization via Semantic Parsing\" or related work), I'd be happy to extract the specific design principles, split methodology, and generalization test categories from that source directly.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 588.8KB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782018875944-xfuudb.pdf]","durationMs":4982,"url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2010.05465"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ea2da41e-2c8e-4518-a7b6-bc1503860f21","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b73be15f-5295-4cd9-a231-c2fe2a90e470","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WCf1HyzCn1QMvbrKkJ9YFK","type":"tool_result","content":"# Memorization Score and Benchmark Design\n\n## Memorization Score Definition\n\nThe researchers define memorization through the **Local Inconsistency-based Memorization Score (LiMem)**:\n\n> \"𝖫𝗂𝖬𝖾𝖒(f;𝒟)=𝖠𝖈𝖈(f;𝒟)⋅(1−𝖢𝖱(f;𝒟))\"\n\nThis combines two factors:\n1. **Accuracy** on original problems\n2. **Consistency Ratio** (CR): fraction of correctly-solved problems that remain correct after perturbation\n\nHigh memorization occurs when models solve original puzzles well but fail on slightly modified versions.\n\n## Perturbation Types\n\nThe benchmark applies two categories of local perturbations:\n\n**Mathematical-level perturbations:**\n- *Statement perturbation*: Replace entire logical statements with new ones\n- *Leaf perturbation*: Replace individual logical nodes (leaf values in expression trees)\n\n**Language-level perturbations:**\n- Replace character names with uncommon alternatives\n- Swap role names (knight/knave → saint/sinner)\n- Reorder character statements\n- Flip role definitions (make truthful characters deceptive)\n\n## Design Lessons for Memorization-Resistant Benchmarks\n\nKey principles from their framework:\n\n1. **Structural variation**: Perturbations must maintain problem difficulty and solution principles while changing surface details, forcing genuine reasoning rather than pattern matching\n\n2. **Multi-level modifications**: Combine mathematical and linguistic changes to prevent models from exploiting either dimension alone\n\n3. **Principled generation**: Use formal problem representations (abstract logical trees) enabling automatic perturbation, solution computation, and reasoning step synthesis\n\n4. **Transferability testing**: Evaluate performance across difficulty levels—true reasoning transfers across problem complexities; memorization doesn't\n\nThis design ensures memorizing specific examples provides no advantage for perturbed variants."}]},"uuid":"90679252-55f1-4e05-aff4-35e60213f3d6","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:46.367Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":484628,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Memorization Score and Benchmark Design\n\n## Memorization Score Definition\n\nThe researchers define memorization through the **Local Inconsistency-based Memorization Score (LiMem)**:\n\n> \"𝖫𝗂𝖬𝖾𝖒(f;𝒟)=𝖠𝖈𝖈(f;𝒟)⋅(1−𝖢𝖱(f;𝒟))\"\n\nThis combines two factors:\n1. **Accuracy** on original problems\n2. **Consistency Ratio** (CR): fraction of correctly-solved problems that remain correct after perturbation\n\nHigh memorization occurs when models solve original puzzles well but fail on slightly modified versions.\n\n## Perturbation Types\n\nThe benchmark applies two categories of local perturbations:\n\n**Mathematical-level perturbations:**\n- *Statement perturbation*: Replace entire logical statements with new ones\n- *Leaf perturbation*: Replace individual logical nodes (leaf values in expression trees)\n\n**Language-level perturbations:**\n- Replace character names with uncommon alternatives\n- Swap role names (knight/knave → saint/sinner)\n- Reorder character statements\n- Flip role definitions (make truthful characters deceptive)\n\n## Design Lessons for Memorization-Resistant Benchmarks\n\nKey principles from their framework:\n\n1. **Structural variation**: Perturbations must maintain problem difficulty and solution principles while changing surface details, forcing genuine reasoning rather than pattern matching\n\n2. **Multi-level modifications**: Combine mathematical and linguistic changes to prevent models from exploiting either dimension alone\n\n3. **Principled generation**: Use formal problem representations (abstract logical trees) enabling automatic perturbation, solution computation, and reasoning step synthesis\n\n4. **Transferability testing**: Evaluate performance across difficulty levels—true reasoning transfers across problem complexities; memorization doesn't\n\nThis design ensures memorizing specific examples provides no advantage for perturbed variants.","durationMs":8260,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.23123v1"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b73be15f-5295-4cd9-a231-c2fe2a90e470","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b672aedd-dfad-4abf-8619-60471da8c6b2","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CnrC74TysJq1VhsFcT1KKi","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"template split paraphrase generalization NLP benchmark question split program split Text-to-SQL\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"EHRSQL: A Practical Text-to-SQL Benchmark for Electronic Health Records\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2301.07695\"},{\"title\":\"Towards Understanding the Generalization of Medical Text-to-SQL Models   and Datasets\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2303.12898\"},{\"title\":\"Towards Understanding the Generalization of Medical Text-to-SQL Models and Datasets - PMC\",\"url\":\"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10785918/\"},{\"title\":\"Confidence Estimation for Error Detection in Text-to-SQL Systems\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2501.09527\"},{\"title\":\"Exploring the Compositional Generalization in Context Dependent   Text-to-SQL Parsing\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2306.04480\"},{\"title\":\"Bridging the Generalization Gap in Text-to-SQL Parsing ...\",\"url\":\"https://aclanthology.org/2022.acl-long.381.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Spider: A Large-Scale Human-Labeled Dataset for Complex and Cross-Domain   Semantic Parsing and Text-to-SQL Task\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1809.08887\"},{\"title\":\"Improving Text-to-SQL Evaluation Methodology\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1806.09029\"},{\"title\":\"Unlocking Compositional Generalization in Pre-trained Models Using   Intermediate Representations\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2104.07478\"},{\"title\":\"Benchmarking Long-tail Generalization with Likelihood Splits\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2210.06799\"}]\n\nThe search results provide comprehensive information about multiple concepts related to Text-to-SQL benchmarking and evaluation strategies:\n\n## Key Concepts Found:\n\n**Template Split**: The template split is a typical compositional generalization setting, where the structure templates in the training and test set are completely separated. Template splits ensure that the train and test set contain distinct SQL query \"templates\" (constructed by replacing values in the SQL queries with anonymized placeholders).\n\n**Question Split vs. Program/Query Split**: Evaluation on the question split does not tell us about a model's generalizable knowledge of SQL. To evaluate the latter, a complementary new division was proposed, where no SQL query is allowed to appear in more than one set; this is called the \"query split\".\n\n**Paraphrase Generalization**: In some benchmarks, training, validation, and test sets are constrained to contain all question templates, but the template paraphrases do not overlap between the splits. Research distinguishes between template-based data (models trained and tested on template-generated data) and paraphrased-based data (models trained and tested on paraphrased data), with template-to-template approaches achieving significantly higher accuracy.\n\n**Compositional Generalization**: Compositional generalization scenarios can be viewed as extensions of template splits, where the combination of basic SQL templates and modification templates in the training and test set are separated, while basic SQL and modification templates in the test set all appear in the training set individually.\n\nThese splits and evaluation methodologies are used across benchmarks like SPIDER, MIMICSQL, and other Text-to-SQL datasets to better assess model generalization capabilities.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"0accf798-4007-4ab8-8aaa-b4ae41e7e05f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:47.391Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"template split paraphrase generalization NLP benchmark question split program split Text-to-SQL","results":[{"tool_use_