ell us about a model's generalizable knowledge of SQL. To evaluate the latter, a complementary new division was proposed, where no SQL query is allowed to appear in more than one set; this is called the \"query split\".\n\n**Paraphrase Generalization**: In some benchmarks, training, validation, and test sets are constrained to contain all question templates, but the template paraphrases do not overlap between the splits. Research distinguishes between template-based data (models trained and tested on template-generated data) and paraphrased-based data (models trained and tested on paraphrased data), with template-to-template approaches achieving significantly higher accuracy.\n\n**Compositional Generalization**: Compositional generalization scenarios can be viewed as extensions of template splits, where the combination of basic SQL templates and modification templates in the training and test set are separated, while basic SQL and modification templates in the test set all appear in the training set individually.\n\nThese splits and evaluation methodologies are used across benchmarks like SPIDER, MIMICSQL, and other Text-to-SQL datasets to better assess model generalization capabilities."],"durationSeconds":8.279609999999405,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b672aedd-dfad-4abf-8619-60471da8c6b2","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
