{"parentUuid":"31d912fa-d166-40be-b96c-784d4a7a0451","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01VfLzxDRHivi5CXvQhbdc7j","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01HXkJQUtfscgrZ6hVHoaqG2","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.06453","prompt":"Extract the concrete design of MATH-Perturb. How do they create \"simple\" vs \"hard\" perturbations of math problems? What is the key design rule that makes a perturbation defeat memorization while keeping the underlying skill the same? How do they ensure surface form changes but solution method is shared/changed?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5268,"cache_read_input_tokens":14743,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5268,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqP1cBEcHW7TZrwwnSh","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"9fd729d3-3dca-4c49-8d5e-eda56e84e46a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:55.379Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"9fd729d3-3dca-4c49-8d5e-eda56e84e46a","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01VfLzxDRHivi5CXvQhbdc7j","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0113N26WGvRr358gYHPSQJDe","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"dynamic benchmark contamination resistant freshness held-out canary string functional benchmark"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5268,"cache_read_input_tokens":14743,"output_tokens":482,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5268},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":323,"output_tokens":482,"cache_read_input_tokens":14743,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5268,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5268,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqP1cBEcHW7TZrwwnSh","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"3aebb044-b4db-4ca9-afa7-28c95386774e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:56.077Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"31d912fa-d166-40be-b96c-784d4a7a0451","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BPkvJFVEZYLEqgyaJM8Ffx","type":"tool_result","content":"# Benchmark Design: Question Split vs Query Split\n\n## The Problem with Random Splits\n\nStandard random splits overstate generalization because they allow **identical SQL queries to appear in both training and test sets**. When a model sees the same query during training, it can memorize rather than generalize—achieving artificially high performance that doesn't reflect real-world capability.\n\n## Query Split Construction\n\nThe query split ensures generalization by partitioning at the **SQL query level** rather than the question level. Specifically:\n\n- Each unique SQL query is assigned entirely to either train or test\n- No SQL query appears in both sets\n- Questions that correspond to identical queries must stay together\n\nThis prevents the model from having seen exact query patterns during training that it encounters during evaluation.\n\n## Actionable Design Pattern\n\nTo measure genuine generalization rather than memorization:\n\n1. **Identify your atomic unit of evaluation** (in this case, the SQL query)\n2. **Split on that unit**, not on surface-level examples\n3. **Verify no overlap** of that unit between train and test\n4. **Evaluate on unseen queries** the model hasn't encountered before\n\nThis approach reveals whether models can compose learned patterns into novel SQL statements—a more meaningful measure of understanding than recognizing previously-seen queries.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 318.1KB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782018893863-nacqb2.pdf]"}]},"uuid":"358332cc-739a-41cc-8a4f-6f5aff9a03e6","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:58.834Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":325701,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Benchmark Design: Question Split vs Query Split\n\n## The Problem with Random Splits\n\nStandard random splits overstate generalization because they allow **identical SQL queries to appear in both training and test sets**. When a model sees the same query during training, it can memorize rather than generalize—achieving artificially high performance that doesn't reflect real-world capability.\n\n## Query Split Construction\n\nThe query split ensures generalization by partitioning at the **SQL query level** rather than the question level. Specifically:\n\n- Each unique SQL query is assigned entirely to either train or test\n- No SQL query appears in both sets\n- Questions that correspond to identical queries must stay together\n\nThis prevents the model from having seen exact query patterns during training that it encounters during evaluation.\n\n## Actionable Design Pattern\n\nTo measure genuine generalization rather than memorization:\n\n1. **Identify your atomic unit of evaluation** (in this case, the SQL query)\n2. **Split on that unit**, not on surface-level examples\n3. **Verify no overlap** of that unit between train and test\n4. **Evaluate on unseen queries** the model hasn't encountered before\n\nThis approach reveals whether models can compose learned patterns into novel SQL statements—a more meaningful measure of understanding than recognizing previously-seen queries.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 318.1KB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782018893863-nacqb2.pdf]","durationMs":5632,"url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1806.09029"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"31d912fa-d166-40be-b96c-784d4a7a0451","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
