{"parentUuid":"b693c013-5e2f-430a-aede-f9ba4b2439e2","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011wQZ8mSQ47yAXucZmy24pZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_019wdPdW4omvSpD4WEats9db","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/counterbench","prompt":"Extract the concrete design rules of CounterBench for counterfactual reasoning. How do randomly generated variable names (e.g., Ziklo, Blaf) prevent aliasing to memorized knowledge? What is the design pattern that forces structural/context-independent reasoning so memorization gains nothing?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3019,"cache_read_input_tokens":20011,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3019,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqQCpPp5r8nxE47k3qf","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"e74ea233-097d-4444-95a4-6d778dc6f7a0","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:12.096Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"e74ea233-097d-4444-95a4-6d778dc6f7a0","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011wQZ8mSQ47yAXucZmy24pZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017RD4cZ8skyyZ1eC7XQdRhZ","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"SCAN benchmark \"jump\" primitive compositional split add primitive systematic generalization Lake Baroni"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3019,"cache_read_input_tokens":20011,"output_tokens":507,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3019},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":507,"cache_read_input_tokens":20011,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3019,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3019,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqQCpPp5r8nxE47k3qf","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"9b9d41be-ecca-426b-a9ff-a21280c95678","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:12.558Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b693c013-5e2f-430a-aede-f9ba4b2439e2","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014TKGpGVf9kWbfnDFYLhTZb","type":"tool_result","content":"# Design Rules for Contamination-Resistant Benchmarks\n\nBased on the document \"Towards Contamination Resistant Benchmarks,\" here are concrete design principles:\n\n## Core Properties\n\n**1. Dynamic Content Updates**\nBenchmarks must employ \"regularly updated test sets\" to ensure models cannot memorize static questions. The key insight: if data evolves faster than training data cutoffs, contamination becomes valueless.\n\n**2. Generation-Based Approaches**\nRather than fixed question pools, use algorithmic generation with seeds or templates. This ensures infinite variation while maintaining consistent difficulty—a model memorizing one instance gains no advantage on structurally similar variants.\n\n**3. Template-Based Methods**\nImplement parameterized templates where question structure remains constant but specific variables (numbers, entities, contexts) change. This preserves measurable capability while preventing rote memorization from helping.\n\n**4. Counterfactual Modifications**\nAlter surface-level features while preserving underlying task difficulty—synonyms, paraphrases, or domain shifts. A memorized answer to one phrasing becomes useless when the benchmark reformulates the same problem.\n\n**5. Temporal Constraints**\nInclude time-dependent elements (current events, newly published papers) so test relevance depends on actual knowledge cutoff, not memorization.\n\n## Actionable Rules\n\n- **Rule 1:** Establish clear data cutoff documentation and periodic benchmark regeneration schedules\n- **Rule 2:** Use deterministic generation functions so reproducibility doesn't require storing massive fixed datasets\n- **Rule 3:** Validate difficulty metrics remain consistent across generated variants\n- **Rule 4:** Monitor for contamination by testing on intentional variants and tracking performance deltas\n- **Rule 5:** Publish generation code openly to enable community auditing\n\nThis approach maintains scientific rigor while neutralizing contamination's unfair advantage.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 1.2MB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782018910361-i2s92y.pdf]"}]},"uuid":"43ce347d-7efb-400a-a4bc-032e9bd074a6","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:17.053Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":1241773,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Design Rules for Contamination-Resistant Benchmarks\n\nBased on the document \"Towards Contamination Resistant Benchmarks,\" here are concrete design principles:\n\n## Core Properties\n\n**1. Dynamic Content Updates**\nBenchmarks must employ \"regularly updated test sets\" to ensure models cannot memorize static questions. The key insight: if data evolves faster than training data cutoffs, contamination becomes valueless.\n\n**2. Generation-Based Approaches**\nRather than fixed question pools, use algorithmic generation with seeds or templates. This ensures infinite variation while maintaining consistent difficulty—a model memorizing one instance gains no advantage on structurally similar variants.\n\n**3. Template-Based Methods**\nImplement parameterized templates where question structure remains constant but specific variables (numbers, entities, contexts) change. This preserves measurable capability while preventing rote memorization from helping.\n\n**4. Counterfactual Modifications**\nAlter surface-level features while preserving underlying task difficulty—synonyms, paraphrases, or domain shifts. A memorized answer to one phrasing becomes useless when the benchmark reformulates the same problem.\n\n**5. Temporal Constraints**\nInclude time-dependent elements (current events, newly published papers) so test relevance depends on actual knowledge cutoff, not memorization.\n\n## Actionable Rules\n\n- **Rule 1:** Establish clear data cutoff documentation and periodic benchmark regeneration schedules\n- **Rule 2:** Use deterministic generation functions so reproducibility doesn't require storing massive fixed datasets\n- **Rule 3:** Validate difficulty metrics remain consistent across generated variants\n- **Rule 4:** Monitor for contamination by testing on intentional variants and tracking performance deltas\n- **Rule 5:** Publish generation code openly to enable community auditing\n\nThis approach maintains scientific rigor while neutralizing contamination's unfair advantage.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 1.2MB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782018910361-i2s92y.pdf]","durationMs":7145,"url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.08389"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b693c013-5e2f-430a-aede-f9ba4b2439e2","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"e74ea233-097d-4444-95a4-6d778dc6f7a0","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019wdPdW4omvSpD4WEats9db","type":"tool_result","content":"# CounterBench Design Rules for Structural Reasoning\n\n## Core Design Principle\n\nCounterBench enforces structural reasoning through a deliberate abstraction strategy. The benchmark uses \"randomly generated tokens (e.g., 'Ziklo', 'Blaf')\" for variable names rather than semantically meaningful labels. This design choice accomplishes two things simultaneously:\n\n**Prevention of Memorization**: By replacing natural language with meaningless tokens, the benchmark eliminates the possibility that models could leverage pre-trained world knowledge. A model cannot pattern-match \"Ziklo\" to any memorized concept because the token carries no semantic content from training data.\n\n**Forced Structural Focus**: The random naming scheme forces models to rely exclusively on the formal causal graph structure and logical relationships specified in the problem. Models must trace through the structural equations—the parent-child relationships defined by the SCM—rather than invoking implicit knowledge about how real-world variables interact.\n\n## Implementation Pattern\n\nThe design works because it separates two information sources:\n- **Structural**: the explicit causal graph (edges, interventions, logical operators)\n- **Semantic**: memorized associations between concept names and behaviors\n\nBy using meaningless variable names, CounterBench isolates the structural component entirely. A model cannot succeed by substituting memorized intuitions; it must instead perform explicit symbolic inference on the formal causal model itself.\n\nThis is why baseline LLMs perform near random (~50% accuracy) on standard prompts—they cannot \"solve\" these tasks through pattern recognition or knowledge recall alone."}]},"uuid":"53f1a3e6-7ccc-4a6f-a8d8-c734ce7b1a31","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:18.079Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":187903,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# CounterBench Design Rules for Structural Reasoning\n\n## Core Design Principle\n\nCounterBench enforces structural reasoning through a deliberate abstraction strategy. The benchmark uses \"randomly generated tokens (e.g., 'Ziklo', 'Blaf')\" for variable names rather than semantically meaningful labels. This design choice accomplishes two things simultaneously:\n\n**Prevention of Memorization**: By replacing natural language with meaningless tokens, the benchmark eliminates the possibility that models could leverage pre-trained world knowledge. A model cannot pattern-match \"Ziklo\" to any memorized concept because the token carries no semantic content from training data.\n\n**Forced Structural Focus**: The random naming scheme forces models to rely exclusively on the formal causal graph structure and logical relationships specified in the problem. Models must trace through the structural equations—the parent-child relationships defined by the SCM—rather than invoking implicit knowledge about how real-world variables interact.\n\n## Implementation Pattern\n\nThe design works because it separates two information sources:\n- **Structural**: the explicit causal graph (edges, interventions, logical operators)\n- **Semantic**: memorized associations between concept names and behaviors\n\nBy using meaningless variable names, CounterBench isolates the structural component entirely. A model cannot succeed by substituting memorized intuitions; it must instead perform explicit symbolic inference on the formal causal model itself.\n\nThis is why baseline LLMs perform near random (~50% accuracy) on standard prompts—they cannot \"solve\" these tasks through pattern recognition or knowledge recall alone.","durationMs":5789,"url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/counterbench"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"e74ea233-097d-4444-95a4-6d778dc6f7a0","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"9b9d41be-ecca-426b-a9ff-a21280c95678","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017RD4cZ8skyyZ1eC7XQdRhZ","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"SCAN benchmark \"jump\" primitive compositional split add primitive systematic generalization Lake Baroni\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Linguistic generalization and compositionality in modern artificial   neural networks\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1904.00157\"},{\"title\":\"Can Transformers Jump Around Right in Natural Language? Assessing   Performance Transfer from SCAN\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2107.01366\"},{\"title\":\"Compositional Attention: Disentangling Search and Retrieval\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2110.09419\"},{\"title\":\"Can Constructions \\\"SCAN\\\" Compositionality ?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.20074\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - brendenlake/SCAN: Simple language-driven navigation tasks for studying compositional learning · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/brendenlake/SCAN\"},{\"title\":\"Can Constructions “SCAN” Compositionality ?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.20074v1\"},{\"title\":\"Revisiting Iterative Back-Translation from the Perspective of   Compositional Generalization\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2012.04276\"},{\"title\":\"Lexicon Learning for Few-Shot Neural Sequence Modeling\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.03993\"},{\"title\":\"Mutual Exclusivity Training and Primitive Augmentation to Induce   Compositionality\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2211.15578\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Can Constructions \\\"SCAN\\\" Compositionality ?\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/395806083_Can_Constructions_SCAN_Compositionality\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about the SCAN benchmark and its \"jump\" primitive split:\n\n## Overview\n\nLake and Baroni introduced SCAN, a benchmark to test the compositional abilities of sequence processing networks. The SCAN miniature language is characterized by a grammar generating a large but finite number of linguistic navigation commands, and an interpretation function associating a semantic representation (a sequence of action symbols) to each possible command.\n\n## The \"Jump\" Primitive\n\nThe primitives of the language are verbs such as jump and run, mapped to the corresponding actions (e.g., JUMP, RUN). Primitives are combined with a set of adverb-like modifiers and conjunctions, resulting in composite expressions denoting action sequences. For example, if [[x]] is the action associated to expression \"x\" by the interpretation function, then \"x and y\" maps to [[x]] [[y]] and \"x twice\" maps to [[x]] [[x]].\n\n## The Jump Split for Systematic Generalization\n\nIn the jump split, the training set contains all possible commands with all primitives except jump. During training, jump is presented multiple times, but only in isolation. The test set is then made of all composite commands containing jump. This split tests whether models can generalize compositional structures to a primitive they've only seen in isolation, which is a key test of systematic compositional generalization.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"e839a427-9578-4235-8e74-2970bf28d2b9","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:23.530Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"SCAN benchmark \"jump\" primitive compositional split add primitive systematic generalization Lake Baroni","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01M92t7Ep1aHMzNMRTfiooK3","content":[{"title":"Linguistic generalization and compositionality in modern artificial   neural networks","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1904.00157"},{"title":"Can Transformers Jump Around Right in Natural Language? Assessing   Performance Transfer from SCAN","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2107.01366"},{"title":"Compositional Attention: Disentangling Search and Retrieval","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2110.09419"},{"title":"Can Constructions \"SCAN\" Compositionality ?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.20074"},{"title":"GitHub - brendenlake/SCAN: Simple language-driven navigation tasks for studying compositional learning · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/brendenlake/SCAN"},{"title":"Can Constructions “SCAN” Compositionality ?","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.20074v1"},{"title":"Revisiting Iterative Back-Translation from the Perspective of   Compositional Generalization","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2012.04276"},{"title":"Lexicon Learning for Few-Shot Neural Sequence Modeling","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.03993"},{"title":"Mutual Exclusivity Training and Primitive Augmentation to Induce   Compositionality","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2211.15578"},{"title":"(PDF) Can Constructions \"SCAN\" Compositionality ?","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/395806083_Can_Constructions_SCAN_Compositionality"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about the SCAN benchmark and its \"jump\" primitive split:\n\n## Overview\n\nLake and Baroni introduced SCAN, a benchmark to test the compositional abilities of sequence processing networks. The SCAN miniature language is characterized by a grammar generating a large but finite number of linguistic navigation commands, and an interpretation function associating a semantic representation (a sequence of action symbols) to each possible command.\n\n## The \"Jump\" Primitive\n\nThe primitives of the language are verbs such as jump and run, mapped to the corresponding actions (e.g., JUMP, RUN). Primitives are combined with a set of adverb-like modifiers and conjunctions, resulting in composite expressions denoting action sequences. For example, if [[x]] is the action associated to expression \"x\" by the interpretation function, then \"x and y\" maps to [[x]] [[y]] and \"x twice\" maps to [[x]] [[x]].\n\n## The Jump Split for Systematic Generalization\n\nIn the jump split, the training set contains all possible commands with all primitives except jump. During training, jump is presented multiple times, but only in isolation. The test set is then made of all composite commands containing jump. This split tests whether models can generalize compositional structures to a primitive they've only seen in isolation, which is a key test of systematic compositional generalization."],"durationSeconds":10.78713995900005,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9b9d41be-ecca-426b-a9ff-a21280c95678","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"e839a427-9578-4235-8e74-2970bf28d2b9","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_013bH5ECb3Lz39iR93zKJmDh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have enough across all five sub-angles. Let me grab one more on the practical contamination-detection / decontamination operations (n-gram, embedding overlap thresholds) to give concrete decontamination rules."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3002,"cache_read_input_tokens":23030,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3002,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqRg5WoZn2eoRXZRwEs","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"8bca3496-a108-4427-a5ba-5720c6acb885","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:26.265Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"8bca3496-a108-4427-a5ba-5720c6acb885","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_013bH5ECb3Lz39iR93zKJmDh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01TSDtqrqjtEENGa5QbSJU8x","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2406.04244v1","prompt":"Extract concrete decontamination practices used in LLM eval. What overlap thresholds/methods are used (n-gram match e.g. 13-gram or 8-gram, BM25 retrieval, embedding cosine similarity)? What are the standard decontamination steps to remove train/test overlap and near-duplicates? Give actionable, specific rules and numbers."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3002,"cache_read_input_tokens":23030,"output_tokens":273,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3002},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":273,"cache_read_input_tokens":23030,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3002,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3002,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqRg5WoZn2eoRXZRwEs","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"41741833-5cde-4113-adfd-4f74bde514fd","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:28.431Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"41741833-5cde-4113-adfd-4f74bde514fd","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TSDtqrqjtEENGa5QbSJU8x","type":"tool_result","content":"# Concrete Decontamination Practices in LLM Evaluation\n\n## Overlap Detection Thresholds\n\nThe survey identifies two primary n-gram-based standards:\n\n1. **GPT-3 Standard**: \"13-gram overlap as being indicative of contamination\"\n2. **GPT-4 Standard**: \"50-character overlap as a contamination signal\"\n\nThese represent the most widely-adopted baselines in practice, though the document notes that n-gram approaches \"may yield a higher false negative rate when dealing with subtle differences in text segments.\"\n\n## Detection Methods Beyond String Matching\n\nThe paper documents several sophisticated alternatives to simple overlap matching:\n\n- **Membership Inference**: Models generate content from test prompts to verify whether training data included benchmark material\n- **Retrieval-Based Systems**: Information retrieval tools identify potential overlaps between evaluation benchmarks and pre-training corpora\n- **Testset Slot Guessing (TS-Guessing)**: Researchers mask incorrect answers in multiple-choice questions and observe if models fill gaps accurately\n- **Perplexity Analysis**: Measuring text perplexity to detect memorization without full training set access\n- **Output Distribution Analysis**: Using model output distributions to identify contamination signals\n\n## Key Limitation\n\nThe survey emphasizes that \"simple test data variations such as paraphrasing can bypass these measures,\" meaning syntactic modifications effectively evade n-gram-based detection. This limitation drives the field toward semantic-level analysis methods."}]},"uuid":"6629dda0-d120-4b9f-9f21-1498e1bfa908","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:35.712Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":303220,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Concrete Decontamination Practices in LLM Evaluation\n\n## Overlap Detection Thresholds\n\nThe survey identifies two primary n-gram-based standards:\n\n1. **GPT-3 Standard**: \"13-gram overlap as being indicative of contamination\"\n2. **GPT-4 Standard**: \"50-character overlap as a contamination signal\"\n\nThese represent the most widely-adopted baselines in practice, though the document notes that n-gram approaches \"may yield a higher false negative rate when dealing with subtle differences in text segments.\"\n\n## Detection Methods Beyond String Matching\n\nThe paper documents several sophisticated alternatives to simple overlap matching:\n\n- **Membership Inference**: Models generate content from test prompts to verify whether training data included benchmark material\n- **Retrieval-Based Systems**: Information retrieval tools identify potential overlaps between evaluation benchmarks and pre-training corpora\n- **Testset Slot Guessing (TS-Guessing)**: Researchers mask incorrect answers in multiple-choice questions and observe if models fill gaps accurately\n- **Perplexity Analysis**: Measuring text perplexity to detect memorization without full training set access\n- **Output Distribution Analysis**: Using model output distributions to identify contamination signals\n\n## Key Limitation\n\nThe survey emphasizes that \"simple test data variations such as paraphrasing can bypass these measures,\" meaning syntactic modifications effectively evade n-gram-based detection. This limitation drives the field toward semantic-level analysis methods.","durationMs":6905,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2406.04244v1"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"41741833-5cde-4113-adfd-4f74bde514fd","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"6629dda0-d120-4b9f-9f21-1498e1bfa908","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a25edca7176cfc694","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01GZcVfQnQwYsrkviq4ojcnZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive coverage across all five sub-angles. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# Benchmark Design Rules for Measuring Transfer Without Answer-Leakage\n\nActionable design patterns for building a benchmark where \"having learned a lesson\" helps on a held-out RELATED task, but pure memorization gains nothing. Each rule has a claim, source, and reliability note.\n\n## 1. Split on the SKILL/STRUCTURE unit, never on the surface example\n\n**Rule:** Identify the atomic unit that encodes the *skill* (a query template, a logical form, a program structure) and partition train/test on *that* unit, not on the natural-language surface example. The classic failure is the random \"question split,\" where the same underlying answer appears in both halves and a model scores high by recognition.\n\n- **Query split (Text-to-SQL):** No SQL query may appear in more than one set; questions mapping to the same query stay together. The random \"question split\" overstates generalization because identical queries leak across the boundary. The recipe: (1) pick your atomic eval unit, (2) split on it, (3) verify zero overlap, (4) test on unseen units. Source: *Improving Text-to-SQL Evaluation Methodology* — https://arxiv.org/pdf/1806.09029 (peer-reviewed ACL 2018; this is the canonical question-vs-query-split paper — high reliability).\n- **Template split:** Replace literal values in the target program with anonymized placeholders to get a \"template\"; force train and test templates to be completely disjoint. A paraphrase split is the dual: keep all templates in both halves but make the natural-language *paraphrases* disjoint, so surface form differs while the skill is shared. Source: search synthesis over Spider / compositional Text-to-SQL literature — https://arxiv.org/pdf/2306.04480 and https://aclanthology.org/2022.acl-long.381.pdf (peer-reviewed; medium-high — drawn from search summary plus abstracts, not full-text fetch).\n\n**Application to your bench:** define each \"lesson\" as a skill template. Hold out a disjoint set of templates (or disjoint paraphrases of seen templates) for the related-task test. A system that cached specific (input→answer) pairs has nothing to retrieve there.\n\n## 2. Train on primitives in isolation; test on novel COMBINATIONS (compositional split)\n\n**Rule:** Present each primitive during training, but only ever in isolation or in seen contexts; reserve all *combinations* involving that primitive for test. This directly rewards a learner that internalized the rule and starves one that memorized seen sequences.\n\n- **SCAN \"jump\" split:** Training contains all commands using every primitive *except* combinations of `jump`; `jump` appears only in isolation. Test = all composite commands containing `jump` (e.g. \"jump twice\", \"jump and walk\"). Tests whether a model lifts a primitive seen alone into novel compositions. Source: SCAN, Lake & Baroni — https://github.com/brendenlake/SCAN and analysis https://arxiv.org/pdf/1904.00157 (foundational, widely cited — high reliability).\n- **MCD splits (Maximum Compound Divergence):** Construct splits that *maximize* divergence between the distribution of compounds (combinations) in train vs test, while *keeping the atom/primitive frequency distribution close*. This is the principled generalization of hand-built splits: same building blocks, maximally different ways of combining them. Source: search synthesis over compositional-generalization survey — https://arxiv.org/pdf/2404.13074 (peer-reviewed survey; medium-high).\n- **COGS:** The generalization set is drawn from a *different distribution* than training and targets specific linguistic recombinations — e.g. a noun seen only in subject position must be interpreted in object position (systematicity), or sentences with greater recursive depth than any training example (productivity). Source: COGS, Kim & Linzen, EMNLP 2020 — https://arxiv.org/abs/2010.05465 (peer-reviewed, canonical — high reliability; note: my PDF fetch failed to parse, so the specific generalization types here come from the first search's summary of the abstract, not full-text — treat type list as medium).\n\n**Application:** Your strongest \"transfer\" signal is: teach skill A on a set of base cases, then test skill A on *combinations* (with each other or with separately-taught skill B) that never co-occurred in training. The atom-frequency-matched, compound-divergent (MCD) recipe gives you a quantitative knob.\n\n## 3. Counterfactual / perturbation evals — change the inputs so the cached answer is WRONG\n\n**Rule:** Take a base problem and apply a structure-preserving perturbation that changes the *answer* while keeping the *solution method* identical. A memorized answer is now actively wrong; only a system applying the learned procedure scores. Measure the *gap* (or consistency ratio) between original and perturbed, not just absolute accuracy.\n\n- **LiMem memorization score:** `LiMem = Acc · (1 − ConsistencyRatio)`, where ConsistencyRatio = fraction of originally-correct items that stay correct after perturbation. High score = solves originals but breaks on tiny edits = memorization. Two perturbation families: **leaf perturbation** (swap a single value/node) and **statement perturbation** (replace a whole logical clause); plus language-level edits (rename entities to uncommon tokens, swap/flip roles, reorder). Source: *On Memorization of LLMs in Logical Reasoning*, IJCNLP 2025 — https://arxiv.org/html/2410.23123v1 (peer-reviewed; full-text fetched — high reliability). This is the single most directly reusable formula for your goal.\n- **Counterfactual robustness drop:** Models that score 74.8% / 64.2% on standard items fall to 41.2% / 36.0% on counterfactual variants — the gap quantifies how much was memorization vs. reasoning. Source: same paper above.\n- **CounterBench — random opaque tokens:** Use randomly generated nonsense names (e.g. \"Ziklo\", \"Blaf\") for entities/variables so the model cannot alias to memorized world knowledge; it must trace the explicitly-given structure (causal graph / rules). Baselines drop to ~50% (chance) precisely because pattern-matching no longer works. Source: CounterBench — https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.11008 and https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/counterbench (peer-reviewed paper + summary site; the random-token design rule is high reliability, well-corroborated across both fetches).\n- **MATH-Perturb:** Perturb math problems into \"simple\" (answer changes, method unchanged) and \"hard\" (requires a genuinely different solution path) variants; the simple-perturb gap isolates memorization. Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.06453 (peer-reviewed; PDF didn't parse, design summary from search results — medium reliability).\n\n**Application:** Build every test item as a *generator* parameterized by values/entities. Score transfer as consistency across perturbations, and report LiMem-style (Acc × inconsistency) to explicitly surface memorization.\n\n## 4. Make contamination provide NO advantage by construction (generative/dynamic benchmarks)\n\n**Rule:** Prefer a *generator* (seed + template) over a fixed question pool. Each draw is a fresh instance with identical difficulty and identical measured capability, so memorizing any one instance does not help on the next. This is the structural defense; detection (rule 5) is the fallback.\n\nConcrete properties a contamination-resistant benchmark must have:\n- Dynamic / regenerable test sets that evolve faster than training cutoffs.\n- Algorithmic generation with seeds/templates → infinite variation, constant difficulty.\n- Parameterized templates: fixed structure, varying numbers/entities/contexts.\n- Counterfactual reformulation of surface features while holding difficulty.\n- Deterministic generation functions (reproducible without storing/publishing a fixed dataset — which would itself become contamination).\n- Validate that difficulty metrics stay consistent across generated variants; publish generation code for auditing.\n\nSource: *Towards Contamination Resistant Benchmarks* — https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.08389 (full-text fetched; the property list is explicit — high reliability) and survey *Static to Dynamic Evaluation* — https://arxiv.org/html/2502.17521v1 (peer-reviewed survey; medium-high).\n\n**Application:** This is ideal for a local, repeatable harness — a deterministic seeded generator means your bench can regenerate fresh held-out instances each run, so a being that memorized last run's answers gains nothing.\n\n## 5. If you must use a static corpus, decontaminate with concrete thresholds\n\n**Rule (fallback when generation isn't possible):** Actively remove train/test overlap and near-duplicates using documented overlap criteria.\n\n- **n-gram overlap thresholds in standard use:** GPT-3 standard = flag a **13-gram** overlap as contamination; GPT-4 standard = flag a **50-character** overlap. Also used: BM25 retrieval to find candidate overlaps, membership-inference, perplexity analysis, and \"TS-Guessing\" (mask the answer, see if the model fills it). Source: *Benchmark Data Contamination: A Survey* — https://arxiv.org/html/2406.04244v1 (full-text fetched; specific numbers cited — high reliability).\n- **Critical caveat:** n-gram/string methods are defeated by paraphrase — \"simple test data variations such as paraphrasing can bypass these measures.\" So decontamination should add a *semantic* layer (embedding cosine similarity) on top of n-gram, and you should still prefer rules 2–4 over relying on decontamination. Source: same survey.\n- **Inference-time decontamination (ITD):** if a benchmark is suspected leaked, detect and *rewrite* leaked items while preserving difficulty, then re-evaluate — recovers a truer score. Source: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.13990 (peer-reviewed EMNLP 2024 findings; medium-high).\n- **Canary strings:** embed unique marker tokens; if a model emits them, it memorized your data — a contamination tripwire, not a fix. Source: search synthesis — https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_model_benchmark (reference-grade; medium).\n\n## Summary cheat-sheet for your \"transfer\" bench\n\n1. Define a \"lesson\" as a skill *template/structure*, not an (input,answer) pair.\n2. Train/test split on the structure unit; verify zero overlap (rule 1).\n3. For the held-out RELATED task, use a compositional split: primitives/skills seen in isolation → tested in novel combinations; match atom frequencies, maximize compound divergence (MCD) (rule 2).\n4. Make every item a *seeded generator*; score transfer as cross-perturbation consistency, and report LiMem = Acc × (1 − consistency) to expose memorization (rules 3–4).\n5. Use opaque random tokens for entities so world-knowledge memorization can't substitute for the taught procedure (rule 3, CounterBench).\n6. Regenerate fresh held-out instances each run (deterministic generator) so a memorizing system gains nothing run-to-run; keep n-gram(13)/50-char + embedding decontamination only as a fallback for any static parts (rules 4–5).\n\n**Reliability note overall:** The highest-confidence, directly-reusable findings are LiMem (full-text fetched), the contamination-resistant property list (full-text), the query-split recipe (full-text), n-gram thresholds (full-text), and CounterBench random tokens (two corroborating fetches). SCAN/COGS/MCD/MATH-Perturb specifics rest partly on search-result summaries because several arXiv PDFs returned binary/unparsable content — the concepts are canonical and well-corroborated, but verify exact split statistics against the primary papers before hard-coding numbers."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":788,"cache_read_input_tokens":26032,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":788,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqSaA6Us51dLFbEuqjs","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"ccfb8770-8d5b-4fb5-bf30-3977a3eef74f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:16:35.348Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
